Considerations for Facebook Messenger in Service Cloud

This article applies to: Standard and enhanced Facebook Messenger channels.

Standard Facebook Messenger channels are scheduled for retirement, and we’re limiting the ability to create standard channels. To avoid service interruptions, upgrade your standard Facebook Messenger channels to enhanced channels before February 14, 2026.

General Considerations
Third-party bots are supported with Facebook Messenger.
Facebook doesn’t allow a business to respond to an end user’s message that is more than 7 days old.
Conversations don’t end after a customer sends a stop keyword. Manually end conversations with the End Chat button.

Limitations:
Automated responses configured in Facebook Messenger aren’t visible to agents in Salesforce.
If a customer starts a conversation by clicking an FAQ, a messaging session isn’t created in Salesforce.
High-Volume Messages
Facebook imposes a per-day rate limit of 200 times the number of people the business can message using Facebook Messenger.
When a Facebook page experiences a high volume of messages over a short period or is sending or receiving messages with many threads concurrently, Facebook may automatically change the page to a high-MPS (messages per second) page.

To avoid conversion to a high-MPS page: Send your messages that aren’t time sensitive consistently throughout the day. Don’t send large volumes of messages at the same time.

Enhanced Messaging for Facebook Messenger
Salesforce offers two types of Messaging channels: standard and enhanced.
New features are available exclusively in enhanced channels, and we’re phasing out the ability to create standard channels.
In enhanced Facebook Messenger channels:
Customer messages larger than 9 KB are sent as attachments.
Agent-initiated outbound messaging is fully supported.
Automated outbound messaging isn’t supported.
title: Considerations for Using Facebook Messenger in Service Cloud
